Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: My motivation stems from a critical gap at the intersection of differential privacy (DP), fairness, and utility optimization in AI systems—particularly in settings where agents express preferences over items (e.g., recommendation systems, resource allocation, or survey-based data collection). Existing work either treats DP and fairness independently (Paper 1 focuses on reducing disparate impact via stratification; Paper 2 studies fair division under DP but with restrictive adjacency definitions), or enhances utility using auxiliary information like frequency (Paper 3), yet none jointly address how to *structurally design* utility functions that are simultaneously robust to fine-grained privacy constraints—specifically (agent × item)-level sensitivity—and provably preserve fairness. The key insight is that traditional utility functions collapse heterogeneous agent-item interactions into scalar outputs, making them vulnerable to both privacy-induced noise distortion and fairness violations when noise affects subgroups unevenly. Instead, I propose decomposing the representation space into public (fairness-critical) and private (privacy-sensitive) components, such that the utility function operates as an information bottleneck: it maximally preserves signals relevant to fairness while filtering out sensitive granular details subject to DP. This approach reframes utility design not just as an objective to maximize, but as a mechanism for controlled information flow under dual constraints. Unlike prior methods relying on post-hoc corrections or stratified aggregation, our method integrates fairness and privacy directly into the *architecture* of the utility function. Furthermore, by leveraging public data to inform the public representation (inspired by transfer in Paper 3), we reduce reliance on noisy private estimates without compromising privacy. This leads to a more principled, end-to-end framework where fairness is not an afterthought but encoded in invariant features, and privacy is preserved through localized perturbation only where necessary.

