Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: The original idea presents a compelling dual-pathway architecture that separates public and private representations to simultaneously achieve differential privacy (DP) at the (agent × item) level and fairness. However, it assumes that fairness-relevant features can be cleanly isolated in a public subspace via contrastive learning and adversarial debiasing—this may not hold when protected attributes are entangled with utility-driving factors or when auxiliary datasets lack sufficient coverage. Moreover, while stratification (Paper 1) improves subgroup utility, it suffers from combinatorial explosion; frequency-based methods (Paper 3) improve utility but don’t address fairness; and fair division under DP (Paper 2) hits theoretical limits under strong adjacency definitions. My key insight is to shift from *representation splitting* to *utility decomposition*: instead of modifying how features are encoded, we directly decompose the utility function into two components—one governed by a fairness-promoting prior derived from public data, and another capturing private deviations regularized under DP. This allows us to decouple fairness and privacy mechanisms more explicitly, enabling modular guarantees. We introduce a Bayesian framework where the utility function is modeled as a stochastic process: a GP prior encodes group-level fairness constraints using public preference data, while private updates are injected via DP-noised residuals. By constraining sensitivity through bounded influence kernels and leveraging posterior regularization, we ensure that individual agent×item changes induce limited shifts in global allocations. Crucially, this approach avoids learning brittle orthogonal subspaces and instead uses probabilistic structure to enforce both robustness and equity. It also naturally integrates public data (à la Paper 3) without domain alignment issues, and surpasses stratification by generalizing across unseen group intersections via kernel smoothing.

